    <h1>üìÑ Project Proposal</h1>
    <h2>Designing Workflow Models for Medical Device Failure Reporting ‚Äì Digital Twin</h2>

    <h3>üéØ Objective</h3>
    <p>
      Pacemakers are Class III life-sustaining medical devices that require consistent monitoring. Traditional methods rely on periodic checkups that may miss early failure signs like battery drain or lead fracture. Our project proposes integrating a Digital Twin (DT) system with pacemakers to enable real-time monitoring, predictive failure detection using AI, and automated reporting.
    </p>
    <p>
      A Digital Twin is a virtual replica of a real-world system. By incorporating IoT-based data collection, machine learning, and failure analysis, this model provides continuous performance monitoring and instant notifications to medical professionals in case of anomalies.
    </p>

    <h3>üõ†Ô∏è Proposed Design Approach</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>IoT Sensors:</strong> Gather real-time pacemaker data such as heart rate, voltage, and battery life.</li>
      <li><strong>Wireless Transfer:</strong> Data transmitted via Wi-Fi or Bluetooth to the cloud-based DT.</li>
      <li><strong>Digital Twin Model:</strong> Compares current behavior against:
        <ul>
          <li>Manufacturer specifications</li>
          <li>Patient-specific patterns</li>
          <li>Historical performance via machine learning</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>AI Anomaly Detection:</strong> Classifies and alerts healthcare providers based on the severity of detected issues.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Flow Diagrams:</strong> (To be included in development)</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Data Flow from Pacemaker to DT</li>
      <li>AI-Based Failure Detection Steps</li>
      <li>Alert System Workflow</li>
    </ul>

    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Feature</th>
        <th>Traditional Monitoring</th>
        <th>Proposed DT System</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Data Collection</td>
        <td>Periodic checkups</td>
        <td>Continuous real-time data</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Failure Detection</td>
        <td>After malfunction</td>
        <td>AI-based predictive alerts</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Response Time</td>
        <td>Delayed intervention</td>
        <td>Instant alerts to experts</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>‚öôÔ∏è Realistic Constraints</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> ISO 14708-1, ISO 13485, HIPAA</li>
      <li><strong>Cybersecurity:</strong> Encrypted data, hack prevention, patient safety</li>
      <li><strong>Hardware Limitations:</strong> Minimal changes to existing pacemakers, battery preservation</li>
      <li><strong>Costs:</strong> AI development ($50K‚Äì$500K), IoT integration ($50K‚Äì$1M+)</li>
      <li><strong>Environmental Impact:</strong> e-Waste from sensor replacement, wireless interference safeguards</li>
      <li><strong>Ethical Concerns:</strong> Data privacy, fair access, AI reliability and transparency</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>üìà Project Work Plan</h3>
    <p><strong>Methodology:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Conduct literature review and gather related studies</li>
      <li>Define pacemaker‚ÄìIoT‚ÄìDT interaction and structure</li>
      <li>Design diagrams and system models</li>
      <li>Address compliance, cybersecurity, and ethics</li>
      <li>Prepare full project report and presentation</li>
    </ol>

